  "prompt": "What were the terms to the Treaty of Versailles?",
  "response": "The Treaty of Versailles, signed on June 28, 1919, officially ended World War I and imposed a series of terms primarily on Germany. The key provisions of the treaty can be summarized as follows:\n\n1. **Territorial Losses**:\n   - Germany lost considerable territory, including:\n     - Alsace-Lorraine returned to France.\n     - Parts of Prussia (including the results of the plebiscite) given to Poland, creating the Polish Corridor which separated East Prussia from the rest of Germany.\n     - The Saar Basin placed under League of Nations administration for 15 years, after which a plebiscite would determine its future.\n     - The towns of Hindenburg and Danzig (Gda\u0144sk) were declared free cities.\n\n2. **Military Restrictions**:\n   - The German Army was limited to 100,000 volunteers.\n   - Conscription was abolished, and the use of tanks, military aircraft, and submarines was prohibited.\n   - The navy was limited in size, and Germany was not allowed to have an air force.\n\n3. **Reparation Payments**:\n   - Germany was required to pay reparations to the Allied powers as compensation for the damages caused during the war. The exact amount was determined later and was initially set at 132 billion gold marks (approximately $33 billion at the time).\n\n4. **War Guilt Clause**:\n   - Article 231, commonly referred to as the \"war guilt clause,\" placed full responsibility for the war on Germany and its allies, serving as a basis for the reparations demanded.\n\n5. **League of Nations**:\n   - The treaty established the League of Nations, an international organization aimed at promoting peace and cooperation among nations, of which Germany was initially excluded.\n\n6. **Colonial Losses**:\n   - Germany\u2019s overseas colonies were confiscated and turned into League of Nations mandates, administered by various Allied countries.\n\n7. **Miscellaneous Provisions**:\n   - Various other minor terms addressed issues regarding the rights of various ethnic groups and territorial adjustments across Europe.\n\nThe Treaty of Versailles is often criticized for its harshness towards Germany and for the way it addressed national boundaries and ethnic populations, which many historians believe sowed the seeds for future conflicts, including World War II.",
